### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

In some scenarios, you can initialize your class properties in such a way that when calling `toObservable` the signal you are passing was actually not initialized yet. Typescript can't always guard against this. This is potentially a pretty common mistake. 

In that case, there is an exception when subscribing to the resulting observable, that is not only very vague, but don't point to the offending code. Making it very hard to debug. 

Here's a code example that reproduces it:

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  template: ``,
  imports: [AsyncPipe],
})
export class App {
  counter$ = this._getCounterStream();
  counter = signal(0);

  private _getCounterStream() {
    return toObservable(this.counter);
  }

  constructor() {
    this.counter$.subscribe((counter) => {
      console.log('counter', counter);
    });
  }
}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```

